Introduction

Why I Chose This Dataset

For my dataset, I chose the paper, Human germline biallelic complete NFAT1 deficiency causes the triad of joint contractures, osteochondromas, and susceptibility to B cell malignancy. I chose a dataset that focuses on B-cell lymphoma as it was related to my BCB430 research. Since my research was on B-cells for B-cell lymphoma, I wanted to look at T-cells and this paper was the perfect dataset to do so. It looks at NFAT1 (nuclear factor of activated T cells 1) which mediates calcium-calcineurin signals that drive cell activation, survival, and proliferation. This paper sequences a human that has a complete deficiency of NAFT1 and analyzes the affect of this deficiency. They also sequence his parents, who have a consanguineous relationship. Sharma et al. (2022)

Basic Information on the Dataset

There are 18 bulk RNA-seq samples from three patients. One patient is the first reported case of human complete NFAT1 deficiency. The other two are his parents who had a consanguineous relationship. Illumina NextSeq 500 was used for sequencing. Half of the 18 samples (labelled as patient) are infected with an empty vector, thus is the negative control. The other 9 samples are infected with WT-NFATC2 which is the test condition.

Each replicates patient and rescue samples were treated with PMAIonomycin and IL-1b. Thus there are 3 treatment groups, one untreated, PMAIono, and IL1b for each replicates patient and rescue samples.

In the paper, they confirmed the functions of NFAT1 regarding cell-death, where the rescued WT-NFATC2 samples showed significantly less resistance to cell-death compared to the empty vector samples. Sharma et al. (2022)

Figure 1: Measurement of percent cell death in chondrocytes. Sharma et al. (2022)

Downloading Data

The datasets GEO accession number is GSE193414. The code below will downloads the raw counts and its metadata into a .rds format. Davis and Meltzer (2007)

# Downloading metadata
accession <- "GSE193414"
if (!file.exists(paste0(accession,".rds"))) {
  metadata <- GEOquery::getGEO(accession, GSEMatrix =TRUE, getGPL=FALSE)
  metadata <- metadata[[1]]
  saveRDS(metadata, paste0(accession, ".rds"))
} else {
  metadata <- readRDS(paste0(accession, ".rds"))
}
# Download raw counts
downloadUrl <- "https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/geo/download/?acc=GSE193414&format=file"
completePath <- paste(downloadUrl, "file=GSE193414_rawcounts.txt.gz", sep="&");
if (!file.exists(paste(accession,"rawCounts.rds", sep = "_"))) {
  countMatrix <- as.matrix(data.table::fread(completePath, header=T, colClasses="integer"), rownames=1)
  saveRDS(countMatrix, paste(accession, "rawCounts.rds", sep = "_"))
} else {
  countMatrix <- readRDS(paste(accession, "rawCounts.rds", sep = "_"))
}

Data Processing

Process Metadata

The metadata has alot of information but we only need the first column which indicates the sample and its treatment group and the column that indicates the replicate number. With this, we can process the metadata to group each sample with its treatment group. I also added a column that corresponds to the column names in the count matrix to link the two data frames together with its respective sample.

fullMetadata <- metadata@phenoData@data
sampleMetadata <- fullMetadata[1] # extract relevant columns
sampleMetadata$Replicate <- fullMetadata$"replicate number:ch1" 

# we need to add a column for the treatment group (ex. Rescue-unstim, Patient-IL1B).
treatmentGroup <- c()
cmSampleName <- c()
for (title in sampleMetadata$title) {
  splitDashes <- unlist(strsplit(title, "-", perl=TRUE))
  treatmentGroup <- c(treatmentGroup, paste(splitDashes[2], splitDashes[3], sep = "-"))
  if (splitDashes[2] == "Patient") {
    cmSampleName <- c(cmSampleName, paste0("P", substring(splitDashes[1], 2, 2), "_", splitDashes[3]))
  } else {
    cmSampleName <- c(cmSampleName, paste0("Res", substring(splitDashes[1], 2, 2), "_", splitDashes[3]))
  }
  
}
sampleMetadata$Treatment_group <- treatmentGroup
sampleMetadata$CountMatrix_colname <- cmSampleName
head(sampleMetadata)

Filtering Out Genes with Low Expression Counts

Rows may have expression counts of 0 in all samples, and these can be filtered out to avoid heavy computation. This dataset there are 3 control samples so we will filter out those where at least 3 samples have expression counts greater than 1cpm (counts per million). Robinson, McCarthy, and Smyth (2010)

atleast3 <- rowSums( edgeR::cpm(countMatrix) > 1 ) >= 3
filteredCM <- countMatrix[atleast3, ]
dim(countMatrix) 
## [1] 26364    18
dim(filteredCM) # more than half of the genes are filtered out
## [1] 12925    18

Initial Analysis

Now, we look at the expression levels of NFATC2, the gene which encodes the NFAT1 transcription factor. The patient carried a homozygous 4base-pair deletion of the gene NFATC2. This variant causes a frame shift leading to a premature stop codon, which significantly reduced NFATC2 transcript abundance and resulted in an undetectable NFAT1 expression. We can see that the samples with the WT-NFATC2 (prefix with Res) treatment has significantly higher NFATC2 expression than the patient samples. Sharma et al. (2022)

# Read raw counts
NFAT1Counts <- countMatrix["NFATC2",]

TMM Normalisation

TMM is applied to normalise the raw count matrix. Robinson, McCarthy, and Smyth (2010)

dgeList = edgeR::DGEList(counts=filteredCM, group=sampleMetadata$Treatment_group)
dgeList = edgeR::calcNormFactors(dgeList)
normalisedCountMatrix <- edgeR::cpm(dgeList)
normalisedCountMatrix["NFATC2",]

We now analyze the sample separation using a MDS plot post normalization to determine the distance between samples. Ritchie et al. (2015)

# Plot by treatment group
limma::plotMDS(dgeList, labels=NULL,pch=1, 
               col = c("red","orange","purple","brown", "blue", "green")[factor(sampleMetadata$Treatment_group)])
par(cex = 0.7) # change legend font size
legend("topleft", legend = levels(factor(sampleMetadata$Treatment_group)), 
       col = c("red","orange","purple","brown", "blue", "green"), pch = 1, title = "Treatment Type", )

Now, when plotted by each replicate, we can identify which of the dots in the prior plot belongs to which replicate. This allows us to see the significant separation between the Patient emtpy vector samples and the Rescued WT-NFACT2 samples from the same replicate. Ritchie et al. (2015)

# Plot by replicate
limma::plotMDS(dgeList, labels=NULL,pch=1, 
               col = c("red","orange","purple")[factor(sampleMetadata$Replicate)])
par(cex = 1) # change legend font size
legend("topleft", legend = levels(factor(sampleMetadata$Replicate)), 
       col = c("red","orange","purple"), pch = 1, title = "Replicate", )
